        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
The CO(3-2) line width is 30 km/s as shown in Fig. 2 of the PDF attachment. We request 15-20
resolution elements, and therefore a resolution of 1.6 km/s.

The other lines may be less broad, and we therefore select a 1 km/s resolution. Through a careful
spectral averaging setup, the total data rate is below the limit of 12 MB/s.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
We want to resolve the dust knots images with VISIR (Fig. 1 in PDF attachment), within 3" from
the central star, as well as the dust condenstation shell at 0.5-1".
The knots have a typical size of 0.3-0.5". These sizes set our target resolution of 0.2".

The large spatial scales (larger than 2") are not critical for our project. We therefore do not
request the ACA.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
Please see also the PDF attachment (Sect. 2) for additional details.

We base our flux extimation on the SMA CO(3-2) image shown in Fig. 3 of the PDF attachment,
that shows a flux density of 10 Jy over the 3" beam (unresolved). From the CO(2-1) CARMA map,
we assume that half of the total flux comes from within the central 0.5".
This results in an average CO(3-2) flux density of 800 mJy/beam for SG1 (0.2" beam),
and 32 mJy/beam for SG2 (0.04" beam). We request 30 resolution elements over the width
of the CO(3-2) line (30 km/s, as shown in Fig. 2).

As described in the PDF attachment (Sect. 2), considering our clumping scenario,
we expect a flux of 9 mJy/beam for SG1 in the CO(3-2) line at a radius of 3" from the star,
that we want to observe with a sufficient SNR to detect the individual clumps.
This sets our sensitivity to 2 mJy, and the ALMA time to 1.9 hours.

The continuum flux density of Betelgeuse measured with CARMA at 230 GHz (O'Gorman+ 2012) 
is 300 mJy, unresolved down to 0.9". In ALMA band 7, we expect 1000 mJy. We make the
hypothesis that this average flux is spread over 0.5", resulting in 160 mJy/beam.

The brightest dust knot at approximately 1" to the West of Betelgeuse in the VISIR image of
Fig. 1c (labeled Knot A in Kervella+ 2011) has a flux of 1.8e-12 W/m2/mic at a wavelength of
10 microns. Extrapolating to ALMA band 7 gives an expected flux of approximately 2 mJy, that
will be easily detected by ALMA with an SNR of more than 50.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
