            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
We aim at resolving the intriguing plumes that reach an angular radius of approximately 150 mas 
from Betelgeuse. For this reason, we select the very high resolution setup of ALMA in band 7
(0.04" resolution).

We want to resolve the plumes and the dust forming shell, that have small maximum extensions, so 
the largest measurable angular scale of 0.4" is suitable for our purpose.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
Please see also the PDF attachment (Sect. 2) and the SG1 technical justification
for the estimation of the flux density. We expect an average flux density of 32 mJy/beam
in the CO(3-2) line.

We set our sensitivity to obtain an SNR of 4 per spectral element at a radius of 0.8" from
the central star, where we expect a flux of 5 mJy/beam in the CO(3-2) line.
Our clumping model is described in the PDF attachment (Sect. 2).
This corresponds to a sensitivity of 1.2 mJy/beam, and results in 5.3 hours of ALMA time.

We expect to detect the 13CO(3-2) line within 0.1" from the star, assuming its
abundance of 1/10th of the 12CO.

To estimate the continuum flux per beam, we consider as in SG1 a total flux of 1000 mJy.
We conservatively make the hypothesis that this flux is uniformly distributed over 0.2",
giving a continuum flux density of 6 mJy/beam (0.04" beam size). This provides a comfortable
SNR &gt; 200.

The presence of the mostly unresolved stellar continuum in the field will greatly facilitate
the calibration and alignment of the data sets from SG1 and SG2.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
